LinkedHashMap in Java

LinkedHashMap is a class in Java that implements the Map interface.

It stores data as key → value pairs and maintains the insertion order of elements.

How LinkedHashMap works

LinkedHashMap is based on:

a HashMap (for fast access)
a doubly linked list (to maintain order)

👉 This combination gives:

fast operations
predictable iteration order
Key Features
maintains insertion order
allows one null key
allows multiple null values
not thread-safe
slightly slower than HashMap
Creating a LinkedHashMap
import java.util.LinkedHashMap;
import java.util.Map;

Map<String, Integer> map = new LinkedHashMap<>();
Example
map.put("Banana", 2);
map.put("Apple", 1);
map.put("Orange", 3);

System.out.println(map);

👉 Output:

{Banana=2, Apple=1, Orange=3}

👉 Order is preserved as inserted

Access Order (Advanced Feature)

You can make LinkedHashMap order elements by access, not insertion:

Map<String, Integer> map = new LinkedHashMap<>(16, 0.75f, true);

👉 Now:

recently accessed elements move to the end
Common Methods
put(), get(), remove()
map.put("Apple", 1);
map.get("Apple");
map.remove("Apple");
Performance
Operation	Complexity
put()	O(1)
get()	O(1)
remove()	O(1)

👉 slightly slower than HashMap due to linked list

LinkedHashMap vs HashMap vs TreeMap
Feature	HashMap	LinkedHashMap	TreeMap
Order	❌	✅ (insertion/access)	✅ (sorted)
Speed	Fastest	Slightly slower	Slower
Structure	Hash table	Hash + linked list	Tree
Real Use Case

👉 LRU Cache (Least Recently Used)

Because of access order, LinkedHashMap is often used for caching.

Summary
LinkedHashMap = HashMap + order
maintains insertion (or access) order
fast (O(1))
useful when order matters
